- `u \ X ∈ A` means that for all `i ∈ u`, if `i ∈ u \ X ω`, then `i ∈ A`

To relate these, note that `i ∈ u \ X ω` is equivalent to `i ∈ u ∧ i ∉ X ω`.

So, `u \ X ∈ A` is equivalent to `{i ∈ u | i ∉ X ω} ∈ A`.

Now, `X` being `p`-Bernoulli means that for each `i ∈ u`, `i ∈ X ω` with probability `p` and `i ∉ X ω` with probability `1-p`.

Therefore, for each `i ∈ u`, the event `i ∈ u \ X ω` has probability `1-p`.

Since the coordinates are independent, the probability that all elements in `u` are in `u \ X ω` is `(1-p)^|u|`.

