lemma bernoulliOn_eq_map :
    Ber(u, p) = .map (fun p ↦ {i | p i})
      (infinitePi fun i ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False) :=
  MeasurableEquiv.setOf.comap_symm
```

This lemma shows that the Bernoulli measure `Ber(u, p)` can be expressed as the pushforward of the infinite product measure `infinitePi` under the map that takes a sequence of outcomes `p : ℕ → {True, False}` to the set `{i | p i}`.

```tactics
lemma bernoulliOn_apply (S : Set (Set ι)) :
    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)
      ((fun t a ↦ a ∈ t) '' S) := by
  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurableEmbedding.comap_apply ..
```

This lemma shows how the Bernoulli measure acts on a set `S` of subsets. It relates the measure `Ber(u, p)` on subsets to the product measure `infinitePi` on sequences of outcomes.

```tactics
lemma bernoulliOn_apply' (S : Set (Set ι)) :
    Ber(u, p) S = (infinitePi fun a ↦ toNNReal p • dirac (a ∈ u) + toNNReal (σ p) • dirac False)
      ((fun p ↦ {a | p a}) ⁻¹' S) := by
  convert MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.comap_apply ..
```

This is similar to the previous lemma, but uses the preimage notation. It shows how the measure `Ber(u, p)` on subsets relates to the product measure `infinitePi` on sequences of outcomes.

```tactics
