Since `X` is `p`-Bernoulli on `u`, we have `P(X ∈ t) = BernoulliOn u p t` for any `t`. 

So `P(X ∈ u \ s) = BernoulliOn u p (u \ s)`. 

But `BernoulliOn u p (u \ s)` is `∏ i ∈ u \ s, p + ∏ i ∈ s, (1 - p)`. 

